    <h4 class="news-story-title">
        
            <a target="_blank" rel="noreferrer" href="https://www.rattle.com/robin-fool-and-his-disconsolate-men-by-william-trowbridge/">“Robin Fool and His Disconsolate Men” by William Trowbridge</a>
        
    </h4>

<div class="row">
    
        <div class="news-story-body col-xs-12">
            <div class="news-story-byline">
                
                    
                        <a rel="nofollow" class="timeago" title="Mar 01, 2022" href="/link/oORUJX/robin-fool-and-his-disconsolate-men-by-william-trowbridge">7 days ago</a>
                    
                    
                
                
                    
                    
                
                
                    
                        &nbsp;|&nbsp;
                    
                
                



    
    
        <a href="/media-outlet/rattle" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer">Rattle</a>
        
    
    


            </div>
            
            
                
                    William TrowbridgeROBIN FOOL AND HIS DISCONSOLATE MENThe snag arose right away: the richhad troops and portcullises, making itvery risky to rob them. And the poorwere supposed to receive the swag, notsurrender it. So Fool decided they’drob the not-so-rich. However, rob themenough and they become poor. Giveenough to the poor and, after a while,they become the rich—a dispiriting treadmill. Alan-a-Dale, the men’s minstrel, tried tomake up a song about it but couldn’t thinkof a good lyric.
                
                
            
        </div>
    
    
        <div class="news-story-meta col-xs-12">
            <span class="sharing-counts small " data-total-count="0">
  

  <a target="_blank" href="http://www.facebook.com/sharer/sharer.php?u=https%3A//muckrack.com/link/oORUJX/robin-fool-and-his-disconsolate-men-by-william-trowbridge" class="times-shared facebook" data-description="William TrowbridgeROBIN FOOL AND HIS DISCONSOLATE MENThe snag arose right away: the richhad troops and portcullises, making itvery risky to rob them. And the poorwere supposed to receive the swag, notsurrender it. So Fool decided they’drob the not-so-rich. However, rob themenough and they become poor. Giveenough to the poor and, after a while,they become the rich—a dispiriting treadmill. Alan-a-Dale, the men’s minstrel, tried tomake up a song about it but couldn’t thinkof a good lyric." data-source="rattle.com" data-title="“Robin Fool and His Disconsolate Men” by William Trowbridge" data-url="https://muckrack.com/link/oORUJX/robin-fool-and-his-disconsolate-men-by-william-trowbridge" data-link="https://www.rattle.com/robin-fool-and-his-disconsolate-men-by-william-trowbridge/">
